- During development, the agent may refer to the documentation to simplify information lookup.
- The agent must follow the current guide when working with documentation.
- After changing any part of the project, the documentation should be updated if necessary.

## Documentation Rules:
- Any documentation related to project functionality must be placed in the `Docs/` directory.
- Documentation files must use the `.md` format.
- The documentation must reflect only the actual state of the mechanics.
- Do not use numbering unless absolutely necessary.
- Do not add numerical values to the documentation if they may change.
- It is strictly forbidden to invent facts. Any changes made must be double-checked.
- When editing documentation, follow the existing format unless instructed otherwise.
- Brief documentation for the main mechanics must be located in the `project.md` file and updated every time other documentation files are changed. This documentation is written in a free, informal style. If a specific file exists for a particular mechanic, reference it as a link such as: [player movement](player-movement.md).
- Core mechanics must be documented in separate files.
## Documentation for core mechanics should follow this format:
The file name must be in English using the format `player-movement.md`.
File content:
># Mechanic Title  
>Short description of the purpose of the mechanic  
>## Files Used  
>This refers to files in the codebase listed as relative links, for example: [Assets/Scripts/ECS/Systems/PlayerMovementSystem.cs](../Assets/Scripts/ECS/Systems/PlayerMovementSystem.cs)  
>Sort the file list first by name, then by hierarchy.
>## Mechanic Description  
>The description should not be too verbose but must be concise and clear enough to understand how the mechanic works without reading the code.  
>Simple and medium-complexity mermaid diagrams are allowed.